So, What is Patch Testing?
Patch testing is a method used to determine how the application reacts to a product. It's a smart way to test a small area first before applying the product to larger areas, which helps to identify any adverse reactions.

How to Patch Test:

â€¢Select a Small Area: Choose a discreet spot.
â€¢Apply a Tiny Amount: Use a small quantity of the product.
â€¢Wait and Observe: Leave it on for 24 hours unless you notice irritation sooner.
â€¢Proceed if Allâ€™s Good: If thereâ€™s no reaction, feel confident to use the product as intended!

*If in contact with the skin, some experience itching and tingling sensations and irritation, which are normal. If you experience any signs of an allergic reaction (e.g., swelling), wash the affected area immediately and discontinue use.

That said, for general DMSO use (without going into all the nuances and additional details), I advise the following:

  1. Start with 30-50% DMSO and see how you tolerate it. When applying to the face, ensure that all makeup has been thoroughly washed off (ideally using only natural cosmetic products) and use a lower initial concentration (20%).

  2. If you have no issue, gradually raise it to 70%. Many find 60% suffices for most musculoskeletal issues, while 30% is often needed for sensitive skin.

  3. Only raise it past 70% if you are certain you are one of those people who are fine with 100% or you are using it for a specific application that can justify a higher concentration (e.g., a collagen contracture, a scar, an internal adhesion or an acute stroke).

  4. If you experience immediate issues with topical administration (e.g., burning or redness) that you cannot tolerate, wash the area with water and try a lower dose. If your skin becomes cracked or dry after repeated use, take a break and hydrate the area with aloe or a natural oil.

Lastly, in some cases, particularly for injuries, DMSO is applied by soaking a bandage in it (or a DMSO mixture) and placing it on the affected area, then wrapping it with other bandages to ensure continuous DMSO exposure. In such instances, due to prolonged exposure, lower concentrations may be required.
Note: after prolonged DMSO exposure, DMSO can cause the fingers to wrinkle like being in water for a prolonged period, but will recover in a few days

Dilution agents

Presently, some of the most popular (and beneficial) DMSO agents which have been identified include:

â€¢Isotonic, 0.9% saline (which you can prepare yourself and is widely sold).

â€¢Nano-filtered deep-sea seawater, rich in essential minerals including those that enhance cellular transport, is a popular carrier for DMSO due to its therapeutic synergy. As seawater has three times the osmolarity of blood, isotonic formulations are purchased or created by diluting seawater (one part seawater to two parts purified water). These formulations are often applied cosmetically, such as 10% DMSO in isotonic seawater for facial toners, or ingested when diluted. They also support gut health, hydration, and tissue repair (e.g., ulcerative colitis) in sterile preparations like enemas or nasal/ear drops and typically are used 1â€“2 times daily.
Note: there is a long history of isotonic seawater being healing and numerous brands of it on the market (e.g., Quintonâ€™s is one of the best).

â€¢12% magnesium chloride (MgClâ‚‚) diluted in water. This is used for a wide range of conditions including scars, hair loss and polyneuropathy (with 6 parts DMSO, 4 parts 12% MgClâ‚‚), sensitive dry or crack skin and facial scars (3 parts DMSO, 7 parts 12% MgClâ‚‚), internal applications such as ear or nose drops, enemas, and mouth washes for gum inflammation (1.5 parts DMSO, 8.5 parts 12% MgClâ‚‚ or saline), wound healing, fatigue, and a variety of musculoskeletal condition (e.g., it relaxes muscles).
Note: when concentrations above 12% are used (e.g., the 30% in magnesium oil) it can cause the DMSO mixtures to harden and become unusable.

â€¢Your own urine (discussed in this article).

Enemas and Suppositories

In some instances, applying DMSO to the rectal cavity can be immensely beneficial. For example, DMSO enemas are recommended for large intestine inflammation (e.g., ulcerative colitis, Diverticulitis, Crohn's disease, or chronic intestinal mucosal inflammation) to achieve higher local concentrations, particularly since oral DMSO will be significantly diluted by the time it reaches the colon (due to it entering the rest of the body). Likewise, prostate conditions are frequently treated with enemas.
Note: DMSO enemas are also sometimes used to effectively administer â€œIV DMSOâ€ for individuals whose veins cannot tolerate IV access or cannot obtain sterile DMSO (as enemas do not need to be sterile).

When using DMSO in this manner, it is critical to:

â€¢First, establish that you can tolerate DMSO, and then start at lower concentrations before graduating to stronger ones (and if the bowels are highly inflamed, to begin with saline alone prior to mixing in DMSO). Likewise, it is sometimes advised in enema sessions to start with non-DMSO enemas before administering a DMSO containing enema.

â€¢Have the DMSO enema be diluted with an isotonic substance (e.g., those mentioned above), as otherwise, it will be irritating to the colon (particularly in more sensitive bowels), with urine or 0.9% seawater being amongst the most popular options

In turn, the most common formulation used for DMSO enemas is a 15% solution (e.g., 75 ml DMSO in 500 ml of warm 0.9 NaCl), with the DMSO concentration being gradually raised or lowered depending on what the individual tolerates and needs.
Note: at concentrations above 15% there is a risk that plastic components will be leached from the enema administration materials if DMSO resistant ones are not used.

Additionally, in some cases, to achieve greater localized effects (e.g., to address a prostate issue), a smaller enema can be used which is held for a prolonged period at a target site (e.g., the prostate). Likewise, DMSO enemas are sometimes combined with a variety of other therapeutics (e.g., the prebiotic-probiotic combination Effective Microorganisms is frequently used in Germany)â€”particularly when treating bacterial overgrowths or leaky gut syndrome.
Note: other gut enhancing things Iâ€™ve seen combined with DMSO include Xylitol (to support butyrate-forming enzymes), lactic acid, material to create bacterial terrain (e.g., zeolites, diatomaceous earth, or therapeutic clay). However, this area (natural DMSO enema combinations) has been barely explored, so there are likely excellent but undiscovered combinations that are superior to those which have been identified. For example, glycine is popular for treating leaky gut, while Urolithin A (a more recent discovery) is a promising option, and hence might be excellent to combine with DMSO enemas.

DMSO suppositories are also often used (e.g., in Europe, these are sold by certain pharmaciesâ€”typically containing 300mg of DMSO), and are quite popular for certain issues, particularly prostate ones (where they are often combined with vitamin E). When preparing DMSO suppositories at home, cacao butter, coconut butter, or coconut oil are typically used (with each one creating a progressively more liquid suppository), with the oil first being lightly melted, then combined with DMSO, and then depending on the consistency of the final product, frozen prior to administration (so it is possible to insert them).

Gastrointestinal DMSO Applications

Complementary Natural Therapies:

â€¢Gallstones: Many dietary changes (e.g., changing the fats you consume or certain herbs) have been reported to help gallstones. Of these, one of the most helpful options weâ€™ve come across is taurine (which has been corroborated in animals but not studied in humans).

â€¢Acid Reflux: As discussed here, acid reflux typically results from deficient, not excessive stomach acid. For this reason, it is often necessary to supplement stomach acid, not just to improve reflux but also to maintain the health of the gastrointestinal system (as so many parts of it rely upon that acid signal).

â€¢Diet: In many cases, having a clean and natural (and in some cases local) diet is needed to resolve bowel inflammation (particularly due to the complications agricultural chemicals cause for some patients). Additionally, dietary allergens play a significant role in many cases of bowel inflammation and must be eliminated (with the most common triggers in order typically being gluten, corn, soy, and dairy). Lastly, sometimes, a low-disaccharide diet can help IBD.
Note: environmental triggers (e.g., mold toxicity) can also set off gastrointestinal inflammation.

â€¢Microbial infections: In many cases, a pathologic microbiome is found concurrently with inflammatory bowel overgrowth (which can be detected with an appropriate stool test). In some cases, directly treating the infection (e.g., with antibiotics or natural antimicrobials) can help (although in chronic cases antibiotics rarely do), whereas in many cases, supporting a healthy microbiome (e.g., by avoiding unhealthy foods and appropriate nutritional supplementation) is more effective. Likewise, other therapies (e.g., low dose immunotherapy to remove the chronic immunological reactivity to the pathogenic microbes) can sometimes be quite helpful. Finally, in some cases, treating a chronic candida infection can significantly improve bowel inflammation.

â€¢Nutritional Deficiencies: In the earlier days of natural medicine, IBD was generally treated by supplementing missing vitamins (e.g., Vitamin A, B12, Folic Acid, Vitamin E, Vitamin K2). However, in more recent times, there has been a much greater issue with mineral deficiencies in these patients, likely due to the loss of minerals in our soil and the remaining ones being bound by glyphosate.
Note: since vitamins depend upon mineral co-factors to perform their functions, situations will often be observed where someone has the symptoms of a vitamin deficiency despite adequate amounts in their labs. Likewise, if vitamins or minerals are deficient, mitochondrial function will often be impaired.

â€¢Bowel Supplements: Over the years, I have seen a few other supplements sometimes help bowel inflammation (e.g., Urolithin A, high quality fish oils, DHEAâ€”dosed at 5-50 mg/day for women and 10-100 mg/day for men). Recently newer ones have entered the market (e.g., anti-inflammatory peptides such as larazotide and bpc 157 or the fish-oil preparation resolvin) which are frequently quite helpful for gut inflammation.
Note: a few of my colleagues also use amlexanox if there is a mast cell component to the disease (which there often is, such as in cases where headaches occur concurrently).

Lastly, as I showed in the previous article, a wide variety of natural therapies can be combined with DMSO to enhance its efficacy, including many which treat gastrointestinal issues.

Conclusion

In this article I have illustrated both the immense challenges those with inflammatory bowel disorders face. Regrettably, their situation again embodies the recurring failures we see throughout medicine to treat the root cause of illness, and that their plight, in turn, is simply the tip of the iceberg.

Fortunately, we are now at a moment where this decades long paradigm can change in the blink of an eye (which over the last few weeks weâ€™ve begin to watch unfold with the CDC). As such, I feel extremely hopeful options like those described in this article will soon become available to those who desperately need them and I am grateful to each of you who has helped play a part in making this happen!
